// ======================================================================
//  xa_multichrom.slim   (SLiM 5)
//  One sexual population, two chromosomes evolved together:
//    chromosome 1 = autosome ("A")
//    chromosome 2 = X        ("X")
//  Everything is shared between them -- the same individuals, the same
//  pedigree, the same N, the same recombination and selection regime.
//  The ONLY difference is inheritance. So any difference in diversity
//  between A and X is a pure consequence of inheritance, which under
//  neutrality must give the textbook ratio pi_X / pi_A = 3/4.
//
//  WHY ONE MODEL INSTEAD OF TWO (the SLiM 5 upgrade)
//  ------------------------------------------------
//  In SLiM 4 we would have run A and X as separate simulations with
//  independent population histories, and compared them only on average
//  over replicates. SLiM 5 lets both chromosomes ride the SAME history,
//  so each single run yields a matched (A, X) pair and an internally
//  controlled ratio. Replicates then measure the spread of that ratio,
//  not the spread of two unlinked histories.
//
//  WHAT IS SIMULATED
//  -----------------
//  Only DELETERIOUS mutations are forward-simulated, and only under the
//  "bgs" (background selection) regime. Neutral variation is added later
//  in Python by painting mutations onto the recorded genealogy -- exact,
//  and far cheaper than carrying neutral mutations forward.
//
//  BURN-IN AND RECAPITATION
//  ------------------------
//  We forward-simulate BURNIN * N generations (default 10N), then let the
//  Python side RECAPITATE: coalesce any lineages that had not yet found a
//  common ancestor by the start of the forward sim. Forward sims do not
//  reliably coalesce at every position (you will see max_roots > 1), so
//  recapitation is the standard, correct way to complete the genealogy.
//
//  The one rule that matters: recapitate at the RIGHT effective size.
//  The autosome is recapitated at N, the X at 0.75 N -- the per-compartment
//  correction that preserves the neutral 3/4 ratio. (The SLiM papers use a
//  single autosomal N_e for all chromosomes, fine for a human demo but not
//  for us, where the X/A ratio IS the signal.)
//
//  For neutral runs this is EXACT: the deep past is genuinely neutral.
//  For selected runs the recapitated tail is neutral, so we keep it small
//  by burning in long enough, and the Python side reports the fraction of
//  each genealogy already settled forward so the tail is never hidden.
//  (SimHumanity's Fig. 3 is the cautionary case: a LARGE neutral recapitated
//  tail can make branch diversity look "robust to selection".)
//
//  COMMAND-LINE DEFINES (the Python driver always passes all of them)
//  ------------------------------------------------------------------
//    COMPARTMENT is NOT needed any more: both chromosomes are in one run.
//    REGIME   : "neutral" or "bgs"
//    N        : diploid census size
//    L        : length of EACH chromosome, in bp
//    R        : recombination rate per bp per generation
//    MU_DEL   : deleterious mutation rate per bp (used only under "bgs")
//    SEL_S    : selection coefficient (negative); set 0.0 for the control
//    SEL_H    : dominance coefficient (0.5 = additive in heterozygotes)
//    BURNIN   : burn-in length as a multiple of N (default 10)
//    OUTDIR   : path of the trees-archive DIRECTORY to write
//
//  NOTE ON THE X UNDER SELECTION (for the biologist)
//  -------------------------------------------------
//  Males carry a single X haplosome, so deleterious mutations on the X
//  are fully exposed in males (hemizygous), with no dominant allele to
//  mask them. SLiM's default hemizygous dominance coefficient is 1.0,
//  i.e. the male fitness effect is 1 + s. This extra exposure is real
//  biology and is part of why the X is expected to lose diversity faster
//  than the autosome under selection -- a feature for rung 2b, not a bug.
// ======================================================================

initialize() {

    // Record genealogies; neutral mutations are overlaid in Python later.
    initializeTreeSeq();

    // Enable separate sexes. In SLiM 5 this is a bare call; the chromosome
    // TYPES (below) decide which chromosome is an autosome vs an X.
    initializeSex();

    // Deleterious rate is zero unless we are in the background-selection
    // regime. Under "neutral", nothing is forward-simulated at all.
    if (REGIME == "bgs")
        defineConstant("MU", MU_DEL);
    else
        defineConstant("MU", 0.0);

    // One deleterious mutation type and one genomic element type, shared
    // by both chromosomes. "f" = fixed selection coefficient SEL_S.
    initializeMutationType("m1", SEL_H, "f", SEL_S);
    m1.convertToSubstitution = T;            // fixed -> substitution; saves memory
    initializeGenomicElementType("g1", m1, 1.0);

    // --- Chromosome 1: the autosome -----------------------------------
    // Signature: initializeChromosome(id, length, type, symbol).
    initializeChromosome(1, L, "A", "A");
    initializeGenomicElement(g1);            // SLiM 5 shorthand: spans whole chromosome
    initializeMutationRate(MU);
    initializeRecombinationRate(R);

    // --- Chromosome 2: the X ------------------------------------------
    // Recombination is set the same way; SLiM applies it in females and
    // treats males as hemizygous (a single X haplosome, nothing to cross
    // over with) automatically. No sex-specific rate map is needed for a
    // generic organism (that was a Drosophila-specific detail).
    initializeChromosome(2, L, "X", "X");
    initializeGenomicElement(g1);
    initializeMutationRate(MU);
    initializeRecombinationRate(R);
}

// Create the population in tick 1.
1 early() {
    sim.addSubpop("p1", N);
}

// End after BURNIN * N generations (dynamic scheduling on the constant N).
// Write the trees archive: a directory holding one .trees per chromosome.
BURNIN*N late() {
    sim.treeSeqOutput(OUTDIR, overwriteDirectory=T);
    catn("DONE  regime=" + REGIME + "  tick=" + community.tick + "  -> " + OUTDIR);
    sim.simulationFinished();
}
